The EOH head office. JOHANNESBURG - Technology group EOH has confirmed that it's slapped its former CEO and other executives with civil claims for R6.4-billion. Under the leadership of Asher Bohbot, EOH was implicated in tender fixing and irregular payments. READ: Zizi Kodwa linked to dodgy EOH payments The group says it's now suing Bohbot and former chief financial officer, John King, for R1.7-billion each. The claim is for their alleged failure to deal effectively with governance breaches and corruption. The group said it's been struggling to rid itself of the history of widespread corruption at the company, including kickbacks for lucrative tenders.